He's expected to say that it is up to Commonwealth members which have Queen Elizabeth as head of state to decide whether they will become republics in the future. The BBC's royal correspondent says that  while such sentiments have been expressed before  the timing of the speech is significant. The next British monarch will be stating clearly that constitutional change within the Commonwealth can be accomplished calmly and without rancour. The Commonwealth was formed in 1931 as the British Empire began to break up and nations claimed their independence. Its stated aim is working toward shared goals of prosperity, democracy and peace. Rwanda and four other countries are not former British colonies. This week’s summit, which has been postponed twice since 2020 owing to the coronavirus pandemic, is being overshadowed by concerns over human rights abuses in Rwanda and Britain’s plans to send asylum seekers to the African state for processing there. --BBC--